<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="reporting-dashboards">
  <metadata>
    <tier>solo</tier>
    <group>pm</group>
    <domain>project-manager</domain>
    <summary>Automated PM reporting: tool-specific dashboards (Jira/Linear/ClickUp), scheduled runs, Slack delivery, BI ETL, validate-then-send agent chain.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>reporting</tag>
      <tag>dashboards</tag>
      <tag>automation</tag>
      <tag>metrics</tag>
      <tag>slack</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-28</created>
    <updated>2026-05-01</updated>
    <applies-to>agents</applies-to>
  </metadata>

  <content>
    <title>Reporting Dashboards</title>

    <summary>Automated PM reporting: tool-specific dashboard configuration (Jira, Linear, ClickUp), scheduled report generation for weekly status and sprint reviews, Slack digest delivery, and BI tool integration (PowerBI, Metabase, Grafana) via API ETL. Report agents query PM tools as read-only, validate data before sending (zero committed → abort, not 0% completion), and archive every generated report. Dashboard data is only as clean as underlying PM data — garbage in, garbage out.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Manual status reporting is the most common PM overhead for engineering leads. Automating sprint metrics collection (velocity, completion rate, blocked items) eliminates a weekly task and makes metrics consistent and comparable across sprints. BI integrations (Grafana, Metabase) enable trend analysis over time that native PM tool dashboards cannot provide. The key rule: separate report generation from report delivery — validate before sending.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Sprint-cadence status reporting requires manual data collection from multiple PM tools (Jira + Linear + spreadsheets), and the same numbers are computed every week.</item>
        <item>Stakeholders need a consolidated view across several projects without PM tool access (executives, customers, cross-team partners).</item>
        <item>PM tool native reports are insufficient and data needs cross-referencing with external sources (deploy frequency, error rates, support tickets).</item>
        <item>Automated Slack digests are required on a fixed schedule (daily standup summary, weekly status, end-of-sprint review).</item>
        <item>PM data must feed a BI tool (Metabase / PowerBI / Grafana) for multi-sprint trend analysis.</item>
        <item>Trigger phrases from a human PM that map to this methodology: "automate weekly status", "send sprint summary to Slack", "build executive dashboard", "feed Jira metrics into Metabase".</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Team of 1-3 people where a quick manual update is faster than building dashboard automation.</item>
        <item>PM tool's native dashboard covers all stakeholder needs — adding automation creates maintenance burden.</item>
        <item>Regulated environments needing report provenance and immutability — automated reports lack audit trails unless outputs are explicitly archived.</item>
        <item>Real-time operational dashboards (incident response) — PM dashboards lag by minutes to hours and are not suitable for on-call.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <how-to>
      <p>Run the seven-step pipeline whenever the trigger fires (cron, sprint-end webhook, manual). Each step is independently testable; never collapse generate and deliver into one script.</p>
      <step>1. Audit data quality. Run a JQL or GraphQL query that lists every sprint issue without an estimate, with status Done but resolution Unresolved, or with status In Progress and no assignee. If hit count exceeds 5% of sprint size, abort with a "fix data first" alert — do not generate the report.</step>
      <step>2. Define schema. Lock the report schema in a JSON file checked into the repo (status enum, threshold table, metric list, archival path, dashboard URL). Every run reads the same schema; ad-hoc changes go through a PR.</step>
      <step>3. Fetch read-only. Use a token whose scope is read-only. Paginate until startAt + maxResults >= total or nextPageToken is empty. Store raw JSON to disk with timestamp before computing metrics.</step>
      <step>4. Compute multi-metric health. completion_rate, scope_creep (issues added after Day 2 of sprint), blocked_count, mid_sprint_status_changes. Apply the threshold table → status enum (On Track / At Risk / Off Track).</step>
      <step>5. Validate. If committed == 0 OR fetch_errors &gt; 0 OR sprint_start_date &gt; today → emit error alert and exit non-zero. Never deliver a degraded report.</step>
      <step>6. Archive. Write the rendered report to a durable store (S3, Notion, GitHub issue comment, or local file under reports/&lt;date&gt;.md) BEFORE delivery. Include the dashboard URL and the raw JSON path.</step>
      <step>7. Deliver. Post to Slack via Block Kit (chunk if &gt; 3000 chars per block), attach the archive URL, and exit 0. For executive reports, route to a human-checkpoint queue first; the human appends a 1-2 sentence narrative, then sends.</step>
    </how-to>

    <section name="data-quality">
      <rule>
        <statement>Validate data before sending any report. If committed issues = 0, the sprint query likely failed — send an error alert, not a 0% completion report. If velocity data is unavailable, state "data unavailable" explicitly rather than showing 0.</statement>
        <rationale>Technically correct but contextually misleading reports (0% because of a query failure) erode trust in automated reporting. Recipients will stop reading the reports within weeks.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Dashboard data is only as clean as the underlying PM data. Before automating reports, audit PM data quality: are all sprint issues estimated? Are statuses current? Are done issues actually marked Done? Fix data quality issues before building dashboards — automation amplifies existing problems.</statement>
        <rationale>Automated reports surface data quality problems to stakeholders at scale. A dashboard reporting inflated velocity because of uncleared "Done" issues does more harm than no dashboard.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Do not infer project health from a single metric. A sprint with 90% completion but 10 scope-added issues mid-sprint is not actually healthy. Combine completion rate, scope creep (issues added after Day 2), and blocked item count as minimum health indicators.</statement>
        <rationale>Single-metric thresholds create false positive health reports that undermine the value of dashboards over time.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="report-schema">
      <rule>
        <statement>Define a fixed report schema before automating. Every automated report must include: status (On Track/At Risk/Off Track), the metric thresholds that determine status (On Track = completion &gt;= 85%, At Risk = 70-84%, Off Track = &lt;70%), a link to the live dashboard, and archival path for the generated report.</statement>
        <rationale>Ad-hoc report formats generate "what does this number mean?" questions from recipients. Fixed thresholds make status classifications auditable.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Archive every generated report as a file (Notion page, S3 object, GitHub issue comment, or local file) before delivery. Slack message history is ephemeral — archived reports enable trend analysis and dispute resolution.</statement>
        <rationale>Reports that exist only in Slack are inaccessible after 30 days (free plan) or when searching for specific historical data. Archival creates a queryable record.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="slack-delivery">
      <rule>
        <statement>Slack Block Kit messages have a 3001-character limit per block. Reports with large tables must be chunked into multiple blocks or truncated with a "see full report" link to the archived version.</statement>
        <rationale>Messages exceeding the block limit are silently truncated by the Slack API without error. Recipients receive incomplete data without knowing it was truncated.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Scheduled reports sent to Slack lose readership within 2-4 weeks if signal-to-noise is poor. Start with weekly cadence, not daily. Include a link to the live dashboard in every automated message. Remove or simplify reports that get zero interaction after 4 consecutive sends.</statement>
        <rationale>Slack notification fatigue is the most common cause of automated report abandonment. High signal-to-noise requires pruning metrics that recipients do not act on.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="report-agent-pattern">
      <rule>
        <statement>Separate report generation from report delivery in the agent chain: generate → validate → archive → deliver. Never combine generation and delivery in a single step. A report that fails validation should send an error alert, not a broken report.</statement>
        <rationale>Skipping the validate step leads to sending empty tables, 0% completions from query failures, or missing data fields. Recipients lose trust in automation after the first bad report.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Report agents must treat PM tool data as read-only. Never update, close, or modify PM records during a reporting run. Read-only agents can run more frequently without risk and simplify permission scoping.</statement>
        <rationale>A reporting agent that inadvertently closes issues or updates statuses during a reporting pass causes data corruption that is difficult to reverse at scale.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="pagination">
      <rule>
        <statement>PM tool APIs return paginated results. Default page sizes are 50-100 items. An agent that stops at page 1 will silently undercount metrics for projects with more than 50 issues. Always paginate until the last page or until maxResults is reached.</statement>
        <rationale>JQL results (Jira) are capped at 1000 items per request. A board with 200+ issues needs at least 3 pages at default size. Undercounting creates systematically wrong velocity metrics.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="tool-specific-api-gotchas">
      <rule>
        <statement>JQL (Jira) and GraphQL (Linear/GitHub) filter syntax differs. Never reuse a query written for one tool in prompts targeting another tool. Maintain tool-specific query templates in .aidocs/memory/ or templates/.</statement>
        <rationale>A JQL query like "sprint in openSprints()" will fail verbatim on Linear's GraphQL API. Tool-specific prompts prevent silent query failures that return empty datasets.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Scheduled agents that run at sprint boundaries may query a "transitional" state: the old sprint is closed but the new sprint has no committed issues yet. Add a guard: if sprint start date is in the future or the sprint has 0 committed issues, skip report generation and send a "sprint not started" notification instead.</statement>
        <rationale>A sprint boundary report with 0% completion and 0 issues committed is always a false negative from timing. Guards prevent misleading reports during setup periods.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="etl-for-bi-integration">
      <rule>
        <statement>Use idempotent upserts (not inserts) when writing to a database for BI. Running the ETL agent twice should produce the same database state. Key on sprint_id + issue_id for row identity.</statement>
        <rationale>ETL jobs run on schedules and may run twice (restart, cron overlap). Duplicate rows in a BI database produce double-counted metrics that compound over time.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>API token rotation for PowerBI/Grafana/Metabase connectors breaks pipelines silently — the connector stops updating but does not error visibly. Set a calendar reminder for token expiry and store token expiry dates in .aidocs/memory/.</statement>
        <rationale>Long-lived API tokens (90-365 day expiry) are commonly used for BI connectors. Silent expiry is the most common cause of "why hasn't the dashboard updated?" incidents.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="human-checkpoint">
      <rule>
        <statement>Add a human checkpoint before sending executive-level reports. Automated numbers can be technically correct but contextually misleading without narrative. The checkpoint is a review step, not approval — the agent generates, a human adds 1-2 sentence context, then the report goes out.</statement>
        <rationale>A sprint with 85% completion but a production incident on Day 10 is "On Track" by the metric but not by stakeholder expectation. Human context bridges the gap.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="ai-agent-gotchas">
      <p>Pitfalls when agents work with PM data and dashboards:</p>
      <list>
        <item>PM tool APIs return paginated results; an agent that stops at page 1 will silently undercount metrics for large projects.</item>
        <item>JQL and GraphQL filter syntax differs subtly between tools — a prompt that works for Jira will fail verbatim on Linear; tool-specific prompt templates are mandatory.</item>
        <item>Slack Block Kit messages have a 3001-character limit per block; agents generating long tables must chunk or truncate with a "see full report" link.</item>
        <item>Scheduled agents that run at sprint boundaries may catch a "transitional" state where the old sprint is closed but the new one has no data yet — add a guard check before generating a report.</item>
        <item>Agents must not infer project health from a single metric; a sprint with 90% completion but 10 new scope-added issues is not actually healthy — multi-metric thresholds prevent false positives.</item>
        <item>Human checkpoint before sending executive-level reports — automated numbers can be technically correct but contextually misleading without narrative.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <commands>
      <command name="install-deps">pip install requests python-dateutil</command>
      <command name="run-jira-fetcher">JIRA_URL=https://yourorg.atlassian.net JIRA_TOKEN=$JIRA_TOKEN SLACK_WEBHOOK=$SLACK_WEBHOOK SPRINT_ID=123 python3 templates/jira-metrics-fetcher.py</command>
      <command name="probe-jira-sprint">curl -s -H "Authorization: Bearer $JIRA_TOKEN" "$JIRA_URL/rest/api/3/search?jql=sprint%20%3D%20$SPRINT_ID&amp;maxResults=0" | jq '.total'</command>
      <command name="probe-linear-graphql">curl -s -X POST -H "Authorization: $LINEAR_TOKEN" -H "Content-Type: application/json" -d '{"query":"query{viewer{id name}}"}' https://api.linear.app/graphql | jq</command>
      <command name="post-slack-test">curl -s -X POST -H 'Content-Type: application/json' --data '{"text":"reporting-dashboards smoke test"}' "$SLACK_WEBHOOK"</command>
      <command name="schedule-cron-weekly">echo '0 9 * * MON cd /opt/reports &amp;&amp; /usr/bin/python3 templates/jira-metrics-fetcher.py &gt;&gt; reports/cron.log 2&gt;&amp;1' | crontab -</command>
      <command name="archive-locally">mkdir -p reports &amp;&amp; python3 templates/jira-metrics-fetcher.py | tee "reports/$(date -u +%Y-%m-%d)-status.md"</command>
      <command name="dryrun-no-deliver">SLACK_WEBHOOK=https://example.invalid SPRINT_ID=123 python3 templates/jira-metrics-fetcher.py</command>
    </commands>

    <prompt purpose="agent-system-prompt-for-report-run"><![CDATA[
You are the PM reporting agent. Treat every PM tool API as READ-ONLY (no PUT/POST/PATCH/DELETE).

Pipeline (do not skip steps):
  1. fetch  → call read-only API, paginate until done, save raw JSON to ./reports/raw/<utc-date>.json
  2. compute → completion_rate, scope_creep, blocked_count, status (On Track/At Risk/Off Track)
  3. validate → if committed == 0 OR fetch_errors > 0 OR sprint_start > today: emit error alert and STOP
  4. archive  → write rendered markdown to ./reports/<utc-date>-<sprint_id>.md BEFORE delivery
  5. deliver  → post Slack Block Kit (chunk at 3000 chars), include archive URL + dashboard URL

Thresholds:
  On Track   completion >= 85% AND scope_creep <= 10% AND blocked == 0
  At Risk    completion 70-84%  OR  scope_creep 11-25%  OR  blocked 1-2
  Off Track  completion <  70%  OR  scope_creep >  25%  OR  blocked >  2

Output schema (JSON, exactly these keys):
  {sprint_id, status, completion_rate, scope_creep, blocked_count,
   committed, completed, dashboard_url, archive_path, generated_at_utc}

Hard rules:
- Never write to PM tools.
- Never deliver if validation fails. Emit error alert instead.
- Never invent numbers. If a field is unknown, write "data unavailable", not 0.
- Never reuse a JQL query as a Linear GraphQL query.
]]></prompt>

    <prompt purpose="jql-template-jira-current-sprint"><![CDATA[
project = "<PROJECT_KEY>" AND sprint in openSprints()
ORDER BY rank ASC
-- pagination: startAt = 0, maxResults = 100, loop until startAt+maxResults >= total
]]></prompt>

    <prompt purpose="graphql-template-linear-current-cycle"><![CDATA[
query CurrentCycleIssues($teamId: String!) {
  team(id: $teamId) {
    activeCycle {
      id
      startsAt
      endsAt
      issues(first: 100) {
        pageInfo { hasNextPage endCursor }
        nodes { id identifier title state { name } estimate createdAt completedAt }
      }
    }
  }
}
]]></prompt>

    <prompt purpose="slack-block-kit-status-digest"><![CDATA[
{
  "blocks": [
    {"type": "header", "text": {"type": "plain_text", "text": "Sprint <SPRINT_ID> — <STATUS>"}},
    {"type": "section", "fields": [
      {"type": "mrkdwn", "text": "*Completion:* <COMPLETED>/<COMMITTED> (<RATE>%)"},
      {"type": "mrkdwn", "text": "*Scope creep:* <CREEP>%"},
      {"type": "mrkdwn", "text": "*Blocked:* <BLOCKED>"},
      {"type": "mrkdwn", "text": "*Generated:* <UTC_TIMESTAMP>"}
    ]},
    {"type": "actions", "elements": [
      {"type": "button", "text": {"type": "plain_text", "text": "Live dashboard"}, "url": "<DASHBOARD_URL>"},
      {"type": "button", "text": {"type": "plain_text", "text": "Full report"}, "url": "<ARCHIVE_URL>"}
    ]}
  ]
}
]]></prompt>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/weekly-status-report.md" purpose="Weekly status report markdown template with exec summary, metrics table, risks, next week focus"/>
      <template path="templates/sprint-report.md" purpose="Sprint report template with delivery summary, burndown, quality metrics, retrospective highlights"/>
      <template path="templates/jira-metrics-fetcher.py" purpose="Python script: read-only Jira fetch, validate, post to Slack, archive locally"/>
    </templates>

    <checklist>
      <check>Trigger matches when-to-use list (sprint cadence, multi-tool, BI feed, scheduled digest).</check>
      <check>Token used for the run is read-only; no write scopes attached.</check>
      <check>Report schema (status enum, thresholds, fields) is checked into the repo and unchanged for this run.</check>
      <check>Pagination loop continues until startAt + maxResults &gt;= total or nextPageToken is null.</check>
      <check>Multi-metric health is computed (completion_rate, scope_creep, blocked_count) — not a single metric.</check>
      <check>Validation guards are in place: committed==0, fetch_errors&gt;0, sprint_start&gt;today all abort delivery.</check>
      <check>Sprint-boundary guard fires if sprint is unstarted or empty (sends "sprint not started" instead).</check>
      <check>Raw JSON and rendered markdown are archived to a durable path BEFORE Slack delivery.</check>
      <check>Slack message respects the 3000-char-per-block limit; large tables are chunked or replaced with "see full report" link.</check>
      <check>Dashboard URL and archive URL are present in every delivered message.</check>
      <check>For executive reports: human-checkpoint queue is used (agent generates, human adds narrative, then sends).</check>
      <check>BI ETL writes use idempotent upsert keyed on (sprint_id, issue_id); a second run produces identical DB state.</check>
      <check>API token expiry dates are recorded in .aidocs/memory/ with a calendar reminder set.</check>
      <check>Cron schedule starts weekly (not daily) and is reviewed after 4 sends for engagement.</check>
    </checklist>

    <verify>
      <step>1. Lint and validate the methodology XML itself: python3 scripts/validate-methodology-xml.py skills/faion/knowledge/solo/pm/project-manager/reporting-dashboards/methodology.xml — expect PASS.</step>
      <step>2. Smoke-test API access (read-only): probe-jira-sprint or probe-linear-graphql command above. Expect HTTP 200 and a non-error JSON body.</step>
      <step>3. Dry-run the fetcher with an invalid SLACK_WEBHOOK to confirm validation aborts before delivery: dryrun-no-deliver. Expect non-zero exit if data invalid, no Slack post regardless.</step>
      <step>4. Run the real pipeline against a known sprint with non-zero committed issues. Verify the rendered report appears under reports/&lt;date&gt;-&lt;sprint&gt;.md before any Slack message lands.</step>
      <step>5. Open the Slack message and confirm: status badge present, completion/scope/blocked fields present, dashboard URL clickable, archive URL clickable, no truncation marker without "see full report" fallback.</step>
      <step>6. Run the pipeline twice in a row. Confirm BI table row count is unchanged (idempotent upsert) and the second Slack post is suppressed or labelled as a duplicate.</step>
      <step>7. Negative test: change SPRINT_ID to a future or empty sprint. Confirm the pipeline emits the "sprint not started" alert and exits non-zero, with NO status report posted.</step>
      <step>8. Audit: confirm the API token used has no write scopes (Jira: read:jira-work only; Linear: viewer-scoped key; GitHub: repo:status read).</step>
    </verify>

    <see-also>
      <link href="https://support.atlassian.com/jira-software-cloud/docs/create-and-customize-a-dashboard/"/>
      <link href="https://linear.app/docs/insights"/>
      <link href="https://api.slack.com/block-kit"/>
      <link href="https://docs.metabase.com/latest/api-documentation"/>
      <link href="https://grafana.com/docs/grafana/latest/http_api/"/>
    </see-also>
  </content>
</methodology>
